04350nam a2200553 i 6805231DcWaAPA20150121155537.0m     o  d        cr150121s2015    dcu     ob    001 0 eng d  z9781433819346 (hardcover)  z1433819341 (hardcover)  a143381935X (electronic)  a9781433819353 (electronic)  aocn900576657  aexclude  aDcWaAPAbengerdadAEU 4aHV9069b.S243 201504a364.36223  aInternet AccessbAEU  aInternet AccessbAEC  aInternet AccessbAEGMCT00aForensic evaluation and treatment of juveniles :binnovation and best practice /cby Randall T. Salekin, Disruptive Behavior Clinic, University of Alabama. 1aWashington, D.C. :bAmerican Psychological Association,c2015.  a1 online resource (x, 271 pages)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aLegal contexts and more -- Juvenile characteristics, political and social climate change, and transfer -- Forensic mental health concepts -- Empirical foundations and limits -- Preparation for the evaluation -- Data collection -- Interpretation -- Report writing and testimony -- Treatment -- Conclusion.  a"Psychologists have always played a key role in determining how the juvenile justice system assesses and treats young offenders. Recent neuropsychological findings show that there are important developmental differences between juvenile offenders, such as varying levels of maturity, risk potential, and amenability to treatment, not to mention individualized personality traits and possible mental disorders. Psychologists must therefore strive for targeted rehabilitation services to avoid unfair treatment and redirect youth to healthier life choices. This book is a practical guide that will help psychologists answer important psycho-legal questions to properly assess and treat juvenile offenders. These guidelines primarily focus on disposition evaluations, which describe adolescent offenders and paths to rehabilitation, and transfer evaluations, which determine whether juveniles should be moved to adult courts. Psychological assessments can greatly influence a judge's decision, so this book will help forensic clinicians consider important external factors, such as local laws and the political climate, and present assessment data to judges in a thorough, understandable manner. This book will also be valuable for attorneys, judges, criminologists, and legal scholars who want to understand the psychological science behind juvenile assessment"--Publicity materials. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2015 APA, all rights reserved).  aElectronic reproduction.bWashington, D.C. :cAmerican Psychological Association,d2015.nAvailable via World Wide Web.nAccess limited by licensing agreement.7s2015    dcunns  a21 44 57 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitation. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration of. 0aRestorative justice. 2aJuvenile Delinquencyxrehabilitation.1 aSalekin, Randall T.,eauthor.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://ovidsp.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&NEWS=N&PAGE=toc&SEARCH=2014-42993.dd&LINKTYPE=asBody&D=psbk403MacEwan University Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/direct.asp?db=pzh&jid=%22201442993%22&scope=site403Concordia University of Edmonton Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=pzh&jid=201442993&site=ehost-live  hUAINzPSYCBOOKS  hUAINmCONCORDIAzPSYCBKSCON  hUAINmGR_MAC_INTzPSYCBKSGM  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6805231-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu2/17/2015xE-BOOKzPSYCBOOKS  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6805231-2001lINTERNETmCONCORDIArYsYtE-RESOURCEu2/17/2015xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSCON  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6805231-3001lINTERNETmGR_MAC_INTrYsYtE-RESOURCEu2/17/2015xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSGM01ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2005042613bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/9255360